#+TITLE: Diffusion Advection Model Analysis
#+OPTIONS: toc:nil
#+LATEX_HEADER: \usepackage[mathscr]{euscript}
#+LATEX_HEADER: \newcommand{\tauE}{\tau_{\mathchoice{}{}{\scriptscriptstyle}{}E}}
#+LATEX_HEADER: \newcommand{\tauI}{\tau_{\mathchoice{}{}{\scriptscriptstyle}{}I}}
#+LATEX_HEADER: \newcommand{\ns}{_0^*}
#+LATEX_HEADER: \newcommand{\deriv}[1]{\partial_{#1}}}
#+LATEX_HEADER: \newcommand{\scr}{\mathscr}
#+LATEX_HEADER: \newcommand{\lapB}[1]{\scr{L}_{\pm}[#1]}
#+LATEX_HEADER: \newcommand{\lapU}[1]{\scr{L}_+[#1]}
#+LATEX_HEADER: \newcommand{\lns}[1]{\scr{#1}\ns}

* The Model

#+NAME: eqn:0
\begin{align*}
\deriv{t}T &= -\beta TV \\
\deriv{t}E &= \beta TV - \frac{E}{\tauE} \\
\deriv{t}I &= \frac{E}{\tauE} - \frac{I}{\tauI} \\
\deriv{t}V &= pI - cV + D \deriv{x}^2 V + \nu \deriv{x} V
\end{align*}

to the moving frame $(x,t) \rightarrow (x^*,t^*)$ where

#+NAME: eqn:1
\begin{align*}
\deriv{t^*}T^* &= -\beta T^*V^* + \alpha \deriv{x^*} T^* \\
\deriv{t^*}E^* &= \beta T^*V^* - \frac{E^*}{\tauE} + \alpha \deriv{x^*} E^* \\
\deriv{t^*}I^* &= \frac{E^*}{\tauE} - \frac{I^*}{\tauI} + \alpha \deriv{x^*} I^* \\
\deriv{t^*}V^* &= pI^* - cV^* + D \deriv{x^*}^2 V^* + (\nu+\alpha) \deriv{x^*}V^*
\end{align*}

* Notation

We will use the following unilateral and bilateral laplace transform notation:

$$ \int_0^\infty F(x)e^{-rx}dx = \lapU{F(x)}(r) $$
$$ \int_{-\infty}^\infty F(x)e^{-rx}dx = \lapB{F(x)}(r) $$

And the following convolution for functions of a real variable:

$$ \int_{-\infty}^x F(\xi)G(x-\xi)d\xi = F(x) \ast G(x) $$

And the following convolution for functions of a complex variable (where $\sigma$ is in the appropriate region of convergence):

$$ \frac{1}{2\pi i}\int_{\sigma-i\infty}^{\sigma+i\infty} F(\xi)G(r-\xi)d\xi = F(r) \star G(r). $$

The properties that follow from the given definitions are:

$$ \lapB{F \ast G} = \lapB{F}\lapU{G} = \lapU{F}\lapB{G} $$
$$ \lapB{F} \star \lapB{G} = \lapB{FG} $$
$$ \lapB{\deriv{x}^nF} = r^n\lapB{F} $$

* Fixed Points

Setting the time derivatives in the moving frame equal to zero yields
the conditions for a steady traveling wave solution, $A\ns(x)$

$$ -\beta T\ns V\ns + \alpha \deriv{x^*} T\ns = 0$$
$$ \beta T\ns V\ns - \frac{E\ns}{\tauE} + \alpha \deriv{x^*} E\ns = 0$$
$$ \frac{E\ns}{\tauE} - \frac{I\ns}{\tauI} + \alpha \deriv{x^*} I\ns = 0$$
$$ pI\ns - cV\ns + D \deriv{x^*}^2 V\ns + (\nu+\alpha) \deriv{x^*} V\ns = 0$$

where we may now take the bilateral laplace transform over the real variable $x^*$, 
adopting the general notation $\lapB{F}=\scr{F}$:

$$ -\beta\lns{T}\star\lns{V} + \alpha r\lns{T} = 0 $$
$$ \beta\lns{T}\star\lns{V} + (\alpha r - \frac{1}{\tauE})\lns{E} = 0 $$
$$ \frac{1}{\tauE}\lns{E} + (\alpha r - \frac{1}{\tauI})\lns{I} = 0 $$
$$ p\lns{I} + \left(Dr^2 + (\nu + \alpha)r - c\right)\lns{V} $$

Combining these four equations to find an expression for $\lns{V}$, we have:

$$ \lns{V} = -\frac{\alpha p}{\tauE}r\lns{T}
\left(\frac{1}{Dr^2 + (\nu + \alpha)r - c}\right)
\left(\frac{1}{\alpha r - \frac{1}{\tauI}}\right)
\left(\frac{1}{\alpha r - \frac{1}{\tauE}}\right) $$

Where again we may apply the fact $$ \beta\lns{T}\star\lns{V} = \alpha r\lns{T} $$ and so we have:

$$ r\lns{T} = -\frac{p\beta}{D\alpha^2\tauE}\lns{T}\star\left[r\lns{T}
\left(\frac{1}{r^2 + \frac{\nu + \alpha}{D}r - \frac{c}{D}}\right)
\left(\frac{1}{r - \frac{1}{\alpha\tauI}}\right)
\left(\frac{1}{r - \frac{1}{\alpha\tauE}}\right)\right]. $$

Now we recall the definition of the complex convolution and this becomes:

$$ r\lns{T} = -\frac{p\beta}{D\alpha^2\tauE}
\frac{1}{2\pi i}\int_{\sigma-i\infty}^{\sigma+i\infty} 
\frac{\xi\lns{T}(\xi)\lns{T}(r-\xi)}
{(\xi - r_1)(\xi - r_2)(\xi - r_3)(\xi - r_4)}d\xi $$

where we have identified the four poles of the integrand:

$$ r_{1,2} = -\frac{\nu+\alpha}{2D} \pm \sqrt{\left(\frac{\nu+\alpha}{2D}\right)^2+\frac{c}{D}}, $$
$$ r_3 = \frac{1}{\alpha\tauE},$$   $$r_4 = \frac{1}{\alpha\tauI}. $$

Here we refer to Cauchy's integral formula, which states that the
closed counter-clockwise contour integral over an integrand of the
form $\frac{F(r)}{r-a}$ has the value $2\pi iF(a)$. Since there are
four poles in our case, we then have five potential regions in which
the integral on the line $\xi=\sigma$ may take place and the integral 
formula may be used.

